        "header": "1Introduction",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2505.24867/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Illustration of the current video-language models’ limitations: over reliance on spatial visual features within individual frame. Frame sampling results in temporal information loss, while the visual encoder exhibits a strong spatial bias. This creates a coherence gap (×\\times×) between well-represented spatial features (objects, scene layouts) and under-represented temporal features (motion patterns, causality), limiting video understanding capabilities.",
                "position": 102
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "2Related Work",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2505.24867/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Illustration of the temporal encoding framework used inSpookyBench.Left:Core mechanism showing how content becomes visible through opposing motion patterns. A content mask defines regions where foreground noise (moving up/left) and background noise (moving down/right) are applied. When animated, the human visual system groups pixels with similar motion, causing the content to emerge.Right:Comparison between moving and paused states, demonstrating how content is only perceptible during animation and disappears when static, as individual frames contain only structured noise.",
                "position": 147
            }
        ]
    },
